{"title_page": "Armenians in Ethiopia", "text_new": "{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group=Armenians in Ethiopia\n|image=Mari & Vakhinak Bekaryan with Armenian school pupils in Addis Ababa, 1918.jpg\n|image_caption=Addis Ababa Armenian school students in 1918, teachers Mari and Vaghinak Bekaryan\n|popplace=[[Addis Ababa]]\n|pop=2,000<ref>https://joshuaproject.net/people_groups/10429/ET</ref>\n|langs=[[Armenian language|Armenian]]\n|rels=[[Armenian Apostolic Church]]\n}}\nThere is a small community of '''Armenians in Ethiopia''', primarily in the [[Ethiopia]]n capital [[Addis Ababa]]. Armenians had traded with Ethiopia from the first century AD.\n\n==Religion==\nThe Armenian presence in Ethiopia is historic. On a religious basis, the Ethiopian Church and the [[Armenian Apostolic Church]] are both members of the [[Oriental Orthodox]] communion of churches alongside [[Coptic Orthodox]], [[Syriac Orthodox]], [[Eritrean Orthodox]] and [[Malankara Orthodox Syrian Church]] (India) churches.\n\nThe Armenian inhabitants in Ethiopia are Armenian Apostolics (Orthodox Armenians) belonging to the [[Armenian Apostolic Church]]. The Armenian Apostolic (Orthodox) have their own church, Sourp Kevork (St. George) Armenian Apostolic Church in [[Addis Ababa]]. The first-ever pastor of the Armenian community was Rev. Hovhannes Guevherian.\n\n==History==\nArmenians had traded with Ethiopia from as early as the first century AD.<ref>{{cite book|last=A. Bournoutian|first=George|title=A concise history of the Armenian people: (from ancient times to the present)|pages=228}}</ref>\n\nBesides the obvious religious affiliation, there is also the story of the \"Arba Lijoch\" children coming to Ethiopia after the [[Armenian Genocide]]. Arba Lijoch were a group of 40 Armenian [[orphan]]s who had escaped from the atrocities in [[Turkey]], and were afterwards adopted by [[Haile Selassie I of Ethiopia]], then [[Crown Prince]] [[Ras (title)|Ras]] Tafari. He had met them while visiting the [[Armenian Apostolic Church|Armenian]] [[monastery]] in [[Jerusalem]]. They impressed him so much that he obtained permission from the [[Armenian Patriarchate of Jerusalem]] to adopt and bring them to [[Ethiopia]], where he then arranged for them to receive musical instruction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://howafrica.com/armenian-genocide-orphans-sparked-revolution-ethiopian-music/|title=See How Armenian Genocide Orphans Sparked A Revolution In Ethiopian Music {{!}} How Africa News|website=howafrica.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-10}}</ref>\n\nThe Arba Lijoch arrived in [[Addis Ababa]] in 1924, and along with their bandleader Kevork Nalbandian became the first official orchestra of the nation. Nalbandian also composed the music for ''Marsh Teferi'' (words by [[Yofteh\u00e9 Negus\u00e9]]), which was the Imperial National Anthem from 1930 to 1974.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://howafrica.com/armenian-genocide-orphans-sparked-revolution-ethiopian-music/|title=See How Armenian Genocide Orphans Sparked A Revolution In Ethiopian Music {{!}} How Africa News|website=howafrica.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-10}}</ref>\n\nArmenians have a much older presence in Ethiopia.  Indeed, one of the first recorded diplomatic missions to Europe from Ethiopia was led by [[Mateus (Ethiopia)|Matthew the Armenian]] who traveled to Portugal and Rome at the request of the Dowager Empress Eleni of Ethiopia to appeal for aid against Islamic incursions into Ethiopia in the 16th Century.\n\nThe population peaked in shortly before the Italian invasion in 1935 at around 2,800. By the fall of the Ethiopian monarchy in 1974, it was around 2,000, after which the numbers fell precipitously. <ref>{{cite web|last1=Aslanian|first1=Ani|title=In The Company of Emperors: The Story of Ethiopian Armenians|url=http://thearmenite.com/2014/10/company-emperors-story-ethiopian-armenians/|website=The Armenite|accessdate=6 May 2016|date=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.keghart.com/Armenians-in-Ethiopia Armenians in Ethiopia - A Vanishing Community]\n*[http://agbu.org/news-item/a-journey-back-in-time-a-look-at-the-history-of-armenians-in-ethiopia/ A Journey Back in Time: History of Armenians in Ethiopia], David Zenian, Armenian General Benevolent Union magazine, 1994\n*[http://su.diva-portal.org/smash/record.jsf?pid=diva2%3A1416660&dswid=-2991 Ethiopia\u00b4s Armenians \u2013 a lost Diaspora?: A study of the role of identity in the Armenian diaspora]\n\n{{Immigration to Ethiopia}}\n{{Armenian diaspora}}\n\n[[Category:Armenian diaspora by country|Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Armenian diaspora in Africa|Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Asian diaspora in Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Ethiopian Armenians| ]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Ethiopia|Armenians]]\n[[Category:European diaspora in Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Armenia\u2013Ethiopia relations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group=Armenians in Ethiopia\n|image=Mari & Vakhinak Bekaryan with Armenian school pupils in Addis Ababa, 1918.jpg\n|image_caption=Addis Ababa Armenian school students in 1918, teachers Mari and Vaghinak Bekaryan\n|popplace=[[Addis Ababa]]\n|pop=2,000<ref>https://joshuaproject.net/people_groups/10429/ET</ref>\n|langs=[[Armenian language|Armenian]]\n|rels=[[Armenian Apostolic Church]]\n}}\nThere is a small community of '''Armenians in Ethiopia''', primarily in the [[Ethiopia]]n capital [[Addis Ababa]]. Armenians had traded with Ethiopia from the first century AD.\n\n==Religion==\nThe Armenian presence in Ethiopia is historic. On a religious basis, the Ethiopian Church and the [[Armenian Apostolic Church]] are both members of the [[Oriental Orthodox]] communion of churches alongside [[Coptic Orthodox]], [[Syriac Orthodox]], [[Eritrean Orthodox]] and [[Malankara Orthodox Syrian Church]] (India) churches.\n\nThe Armenian inhabitants in Ethiopia are Armenian Apostolics (Orthodox Armenians) belonging to the [[Armenian Apostolic Church]]. The Armenian Apostolic (Orthodox) have their own church, Sourp Kevork (St. George) Armenian Apostolic Church in [[Addis Ababa]]. The first-ever pastor of the Armenian community was Rev. Hovhannes Guevherian.\n\n==History==\nArmenians had traded with Ethiopia from as early as the first century AD.<ref>{{cite book|last=A. Bournoutian|first=George|title=A concise history of the Armenian people: (from ancient times to the present)|pages=228}}</ref>\n\nBesides the obvious religious affiliation, there is also the story of the \"Arba Lijoch\" children coming to Ethiopia after the [[Armenian Genocide]]. Arba Lijoch were a group of 40 Armenian [[orphan]]s who had escaped from the atrocities in [[Turkey]], and were afterwards adopted by [[Haile Selassie I of Ethiopia]], then [[Crown Prince]] [[Ras (title)|Ras]] Tafari. He had met them while visiting the [[Armenian Apostolic Church|Armenian]] [[monastery]] in [[Jerusalem]]. They impressed him so much that he obtained permission from the [[Armenian Patriarchate of Jerusalem]] to adopt and bring them to [[Ethiopia]], where he then arranged for them to receive musical instruction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://howafrica.com/armenian-genocide-orphans-sparked-revolution-ethiopian-music/|title=See How Armenian Genocide Orphans Sparked A Revolution In Ethiopian Music {{!}} How Africa News|website=howafrica.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-10}}</ref>\n\nThe Arba Lijoch arrived in [[Addis Ababa]] in 1924, and along with their bandleader Kevork Nalbandian became the first official orchestra of the nation. Nalbandian also composed the music for ''Marsh Teferi'' (words by [[Yofteh\u00e9 Negus\u00e9]]), which was the Imperial National Anthem from 1930 to 1974.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://howafrica.com/armenian-genocide-orphans-sparked-revolution-ethiopian-music/|title=See How Armenian Genocide Orphans Sparked A Revolution In Ethiopian Music {{!}} How Africa News|website=howafrica.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-10}}</ref>\n\nArmenians have a much older presence in Ethiopia.  Indeed, one of the first recorded diplomatic missions to Europe from Ethiopia was led by [[Mateus (Ethiopia)|Matthew the Armenian]] who traveled to Portugal and Rome at the request of the Dowager Empress Eleni of Ethiopia to appeal for aid against Islamic incursions into Ethiopia in the 16th Century.\n\nThe population peaked in shortly before the Italian invasion in 1935 at around 2,800. By the fall of the Ethiopian monarchy in 1974, it was around 2,000, after which the numbers fell precipitously. <ref>{{cite web|last1=Aslanian|first1=Ani|title=In The Company of Emperors: The Story of Ethiopian Armenians|url=http://thearmenite.com/2014/10/company-emperors-story-ethiopian-armenians/|website=The Armenite|accessdate=6 May 2016|date=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.keghart.com/Armenians-in-Ethiopia Armenians in Ethiopia - A Vanishing Community]\n*[http://agbu.org/news-item/a-journey-back-in-time-a-look-at-the-history-of-armenians-in-ethiopia/ A Journey Back in Time: History of Armenians in Ethiopia], David Zenian, Armenian General Benevolent Union magazine, 1994\n\n{{Immigration to Ethiopia}}\n{{Armenian diaspora}}\n\n[[Category:Armenian diaspora by country|Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Armenian diaspora in Africa|Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Asian diaspora in Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Ethiopian Armenians| ]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Ethiopia|Armenians]]\n[[Category:European diaspora in Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Armenia\u2013Ethiopia relations]]\n", "name_user": "Aradasthlm", "label": "safe", "comment": "I added a link on the community", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Armenians_in_Ethiopia"}
{"title_page": "2020 Tour (Bon Jovi)", "text_new": "{{Infobox concert tour|concert_tour_name=2020 Tour|image=|image_caption=|image_size=250px|border=yes|artist=[[Bon Jovi]]|album=''[[Bon Jovi: 2020]]''|start_date={{Startdate|2020|06|10}}|end_date={{Enddate|2020|07|28}}|number_of_legs=1|number_of_shows=0 (Canceled) |location=[[North America]]|last_tour=[[This House Is Not for Sale Tour]]<br>(2017\u201319)|this_tour='''2020 Tour'''<br>(2020)}}\n\nThe '''2020 Tour''' was supposed to be the nineteenth upcoming concert tour by American rock band [[Bon Jovi]], in support of their album ''[[Bon Jovi: 2020]]'' (2020). The tour was scheduled to commence on June 10, 2020 in [[Tacoma, Washington]] at the [[Tacoma Dome]] and scheduled to conclude on July 28, 2020 with two nights at [[Madison Square Garden]]. The tour was canceled on April 20, 2020 due to the events of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/touring/8548089/bon-jovi-2020-summer-tour-bryan-adams-dates|title=Bon Jovi Hitting the Road With Bryan Adams For 2020 Tour: See the Dates|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref><ref name=\"Variety\">{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/bon-jovi-cancels-2020-tour-fans-refund-1234584911/|title=Bon Jovi Cancels 2020 Tour, Rather Than Postponing: 'This Will Enable Ticketholders to Get Refunds'|last=Angermiller|first=Michele|date=April 20, 2020|website=Variety|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Ticket sales ==\nTickets went on general sale to the public on January 24, 2020 at 10 a.m. Pre-sales began on January 21, 2020 and ended on January 23, 2020 at 10 p.m.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bonjovi.com/blogs/news/bon-jovi-2020-tour-announcement|title=Bon Jovi 2020 Tour Announcement {{!}} News|last=Store|first=Bon Jovi Official Online|website=Bon Jovi Official Online Store|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> A second night was added in [[Boston]] at the [[TD Garden]] due to overwhelming popular demand after the first night sold out; the additional show will take place on July 17th with pre-sales beginning on March 2, 2020 at 10 a.m. Tickets for the general public will go on sale March 6 at 10 a.m.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boston.com/events/events/2020/02/26/bon-jovi-boston-concert-2020|title=Bon Jovi adds second Boston concert in summer 2020 {{!}} Boston.com|website=www.boston.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n== Cancellation ==\nOn April 20, 2020, Bon Jovi announced that the 2020 Tour had been canceled due to the events of [[COVID-19]].<ref name=\"Variety\"/>\n\n== Tour Dates ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! width=\"175\" |Date\n! width=\"150\" |City\n! width=\"150\" |Country\n! width=\"250\" |Venue\n! width=\"150\" |Support\n! width=\"150\" |Attendance\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\" style=\"background:#DFDFDF;\" |North America<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/touring/8548089/bon-jovi-2020-summer-tour-bryan-adams-dates|title=Bon Jovi Hitting the Road With Bryan Adams For 2020 Tour: See the Dates|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|June 10, 2020\n|[[Tacoma, Washington|Tacoma]]\n| rowspan=\"9\" |[[United States]]\n|[[Tacoma Dome]]\n| rowspan=\"5\" |[[Bryan Adams]]\n|rowspan=\"20\" |Canceled\n|-\n|June 11, 2020\n|[[Portland, Oregon|Portland]]\n|[[Moda Center]]\n|-\n|June 13, 2020\n|[[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]]\n|[[Golden 1 Center]]\n|-\n|June 16, 2020\n|[[San Jose, California|San Jose]]\n|[[SAP Center]]\n|-\n|June 18, 2020\n|[[Inglewood, California|Inglewood]]\n|[[The Forum (Inglewood, California)|The Forum]]\n|-\n|June 20, 2020\n|[[Las Vegas]]\n|[[T-Mobile Arena]]\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n|June 23, 2020\n|[[San Antonio]]\n|[[AT&T Center]]\n| rowspan=\"3\" |Bryan Adams\n|-\n|June 25, 2020\n|[[Dallas]]\n|[[American Airlines Center]]\n|-\n|June 26, 2020\n|[[Tulsa, Oklahoma|Tulsa]]\n|[[BOK Center]]\n|-\n|July 10, 2020\n|[[Toronto]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Canada]]\n|[[Scotiabank